1095332465940393984.text: translation is not a 1:1 activity. and the gaps that present themselves in translation work aren't just negative space- they are really interesting facts about how concepts can be expressed! i think this is some of the most amazing work out there

1095332465038651393.text: there's an idea that if we all spoke the same language that we could instantly share *all the knowledge*. the *all* bit there is wrong tho. one form of expression will never be able to express it all. i'm not ready to give up on that body of knowledge yet!

1095332464220868608.text: i never want one programming language to win. same for all other types of language. multiple modes of expression grow the surface area of investigation about expression in general! i think the density of information in the emergent differences is *awesome* and hugely important

1095332462857641985.text: in the (impossible IMO) future where everyone uses one language, we would have a HUGE blindspot because of the lack of *space* to explore this dimension of expression. choosing one language would be a calcification- the pool of knowledge we could potentially seek would be smaller

1095332461372878849.text: without that diversity of expression, a lot of the insights we were able to draw would have been very difficult to *see*, there was knowledge- *expressed in the differences*

1095332460018061313.text: being able to look at that diversity was extremely valuable- it said things about the cultures that spoke those languages, it also said things about *the content itself*

1095332459133259776.text:
the expression of human knowledge fell along very different structures- and this was fascinating and illuminating.

this is similar to how a program can be expressed in very different ways by different programming languages.

1095332458432815104.text: part of the reason this work was so fascinating is that all the language wikipedias had content structures that differed- some in large ways, some in small way! the categories were different- what was a page vs a section was different!

1095332457765896192.text:
a naive ashley had thought that wikipedia in other languages were just direct translations of the english. i believed that the pages were the same. the relative structure was the same. 

this isn't true at all!

1095332456431927301.text: i think one of my most eye opening experiences was working at Northwestern Univ creating unified interactive visualizations of the multi-lingual wikipedia platform

1095303209130909696.text:
if you really want to help- you can both promote coping strategies AND the work of folks changing the status quo. you should do both. help who you can now in the moment, but also fight for a future that's accessible and better for EVERYONE.

fin

1095302835024089088.text: anyways- coping strategies are good, but they are that. coping strategies. when presented as such they are useful. when not- they are actively harmful *even* if they work *because* they don't seek to change the fundamental inequity of the status quo.

1095302475748466688.text: so in the end, the coping strategies hurt the revolutionary work of changing the status quo when they aren't viewed as temporary bandaids but as a new ideal that folks should aim for.

1095302075192434688.text: this disruption is revolutionary work. it takes time. as a result- the iterative strategies are useful! the coping mechanisms can help folks in the moment. but they still promote the fundamental inequity of the status quo they help (some) folks cope with

1095302074240286721.text: the other camps, folks that encourage i18n work and third wave (or whatever wave we're on) feminists, want to actively disrupt the status quo. this is because they identify that the coping strategies are not fully accessible.

1095302073602768896.text:
they seek to promote iterative strategies. the issue here is that the iterative strategies perpetuate a status quo that everyone agrees creates problems.

iterative strategies don't disrupt the status quo. they perpetuate it, via assimilation.

1095302072801640449.text: both the "learn english" and second wave feminist camps serve to establish coping mechanisms to address an identified status quo. it is indisputable that these coping mechanisms are at least vaguely effective. it is also indisputable that they are not accessible to everyone.

1095302072172535808.text: similarly, second wave feminists often espouse picking up masculine traits like assertive/aggressive conversation style and other "lean in" traits

1095302071476281346.text: in this discourse there is an argument that we should default to english because it is how folks for whom english is not their primary language can gain success quickly in the current state of programming

1076169007210946560.text: this is all about behavior that's sub-CoC violation level. a type of behavior that moderation teams still struggle to enforce- mostly because it's so hard to write a document that comprehensively prescribes it.

1076168763198844928.text:
on other days, i feel like swift moderation that says "you feedback is valid but in order for it to be considered you need to phrase it more constructively" is what's important.
